ortant than examining the novelist's shaping of male characters and his richly metaphorical language as an experiment in gender and sexual theorizing. Just as an author's creations can be animated by his or her own sexuality, Person contends, James's sexuality may be most usefully understood as something primarily aesthetic and textual. As Person shows in chapters devoted to some of this author's best-known novels—Roderick Hudson, The American, The Portrait of a Lady, The Bostonians, The Ambassadors, The Golden Bowl—James conducts a series of experiments in gender/sexual construction and deconstruction. He delights in positioning his male characters so that their gender and sexual orientations are reversed, ambiguous, and even multiple. Ultimately, he keeps male identity in suspense by pluralizing male subjectivity.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aHomosexuality and literaturezUnited States. 0aMasculinity in literature. 0aMen in literature. 0aPsychological fiction, AmericanxHistory and criticism. 0aSex in literature. 0aSex role in literature. 4aLesbian. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / American / General.2bisacsh  aCultural Studies.  aGay Studies.  aGender Studies.  aLesbian Studies.  aLiterature.  aQueer Studies.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn Press eBook Package Complete Collectionz978311041345808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn Press eBook-Package Literaturez978311041354008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Pennsylvania Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311045954840uhttps://doi.org/10.9783/978081220323340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780812203233423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780812203233.jpg  a978-3-11-041345-8  Penn Press eBook Package Complete Collection  a978-3-11-041354-0  Penn Press eBook